04994nam a22006975i 9781487580247DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191974onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875802477 a10.3138/97814875802472doi  a(DE-B1597)528033  a(OCoLC)1129172569  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHF298b.S73 7aBUS0790002bisacsh04a380.1/06/27135412231 aStanford, G.H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTo Serve the Community :bThe Story of Toronto's Board of Trade /cG.H. Stanford. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1974  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Beginnings -- t2. Consolidation -- t3. The Nineties -- t4. Empire Trade -- t5. Transportation -- t6. World War I -- t7. The Twenties -- t8. Toward a National Organization -- t9. Depression -- t10. World War II -- t11. The New City -- t12. Into the Future -- tAPPENDIX. Presidents of the Toronto Board of Trade, 1845-1974 -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is little doubt that Metropolitan Toronto would be a very different place today if it were not for the continuous active concern and influence of its Board of Trade. Rooted in the common soil commerce and industry, the Board and the community have grown along parallel lines over the past 140 years; their histories are inseparable and the story of the Board of Trade inevitably reveals and defines the forces which shaped Toronto and are responsible for its present character. To Serve the Community tells this story for the first time. Based on contemporary records, it is a soundly factual, immensely readable account of the Board's activities and development from inception to the present day. Originally a convocation of businessmen who needed a meeting place to conduct trade, discuss matters of mutual concern, and protects their working environment, the Board gradually expanded its scope over the years. As Toronto grew, so too the Board branched out, taking a keen interest in all aspects of the growth and establishing itself as an influential body deeply concerned with the well-being of the community as a whole. Within the formal structure of the organization, sections were formed responsible for a variety of commercial interests. Areas such as transportation, harbour development, immigration, education, urban planning, tourism, banking, charities, taxes, tariffs, municipal administration, and more were profoundly affected by the opinions and actions of the Board. Although essentially an organization of Toronto businessmen, the Board has never taken a parochial stance, but has involved itself in provincial and national matters, recognizing that wider issues invariably affect the condition of its immediate jurisdiction. Members have actively participated on many commissions, committees and representative delegations, always keeping the view-point and interests of the private sector in the forefront of community development. Perhaps the most significant achievement of the Board has been its ability to attract consistently to its service so many dedicated and capable people prepared to volunteer their time and abilities to the broad concerns of their community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Government & Business.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148758024740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487580247423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487580247.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Pa